u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-us-canada-47587540\"\u003Etalking\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis seemingly magical feat is especially impressive in predominantly monolingual countries like the United States and the United Kingdom (where, respectively, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.amacad.org\u002Fsites\u002Fdefault\u002Ffiles\u002Facademy\u002Fmultimedia\u002Fpdfs\u002Fpublications\u002Fresearchpapersmonographs\u002FState-of-Languages-in-US.pdf\"\u003Eroughly 80%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fesol.britishcouncil.org\u002Fcontent\u002Flearners\u002Fskills\u002Freading\u002Fbritish-worst-learning-languages\"\u003E62%\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of the population speaks only English). But where such enviable talent creates an \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theatlantic.com\u002Fhealth\u002Farchive\u002F2019\u002F04\u002Fpete-buttigiegs-polygot-magic\u002F588169\u002F\"\u003Eaura of mystique\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, it also inevitably arouses curiosity. When former US Senator Claire McCaskill asked Buttigieg to comment on his language-speaking ability in a 14 February instalment of MSNBC&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.youtube.com\u002Fwatch?v=yxH30Nx17H4\"\u003EMorning Joe,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E he replied: &ldquo;it depends what you mean by speak!&rdquo; and added that he can &ldquo;still kind of read a newspaper in Norwegian&hellip; but only slowly&rdquo; and that he has gotten &ldquo;rusty&rdquo; in his Arabic and Dari. That shows humility, but not so much that Buttigieg and his camp definitively dismiss the polyglot rumours.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is not to deride Mayor Buttigieg. His perceived fluency interests me because I&rsquo;m a former language teacher &ndash; having taught English for 11 years in Japan and Italy &ndash; and I am also a Cambridge English exam speaking examiner; a role which requires me to dissect variables in candidates&rsquo; second language production such as pronunciation, discourse management, and grammatical range. Buttigieg is clearly fascinated by languages, willing to learn, and is brave enough to practice with native speakers on television &ndash; qualities that would have made him the star of my classroom. But &ndash; like so many of my ex-students who expected to go from &ldquo;beginner&rdquo; to &ldquo;native&rdquo; proficiency in two months &ndash; Buttigieg may have underestimated what it means to &ldquo;speak&rdquo; a language.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI can relate all too well to overestimating one&rsquo;s own abilities. A &ldquo;heritage speaker&rdquo; of Italian, I&rsquo;d been living in Italy for two years when I overheard a receptionist refer me to me as &ldquo;that foreigner who doesn&rsquo;t speak Italian&rdquo;. I was confused, then gutted. That one casual sentence launched a journey that resulted in my being forced to acknowledge that while I had grown up speaking Italian at home and was \u003Cem\u003Efluent\u003C\u002Fem\u003E, I was not by any means \u003Cem\u003Eproficient\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8rf9"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat does the word &ldquo;fluent&rdquo; actually mean? In lay circles, this term has come to equal \"native-level proficient\", with no grey area between the bumbling beginner and the mellifluous master. An outsider overhearing a conversation in a foreign language only hears a fog of sounds, thus perceiving \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fmashable.com\u002Farticle\u002Fpete-buttigieg-notre-dame-cathedral-french-response\u002F?europe=true\"\u003Eanyone who can cobble together a sentence as &ldquo;fluent&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut Daniel Morgan, head of learning development at the Shenker Institutes of English &ndash; a popular chain of English schools in Italy &ndash; says that \u003Cem\u003Efluency\u003C\u002Fem\u003E actually refers to how &ldquo;smoothly&rdquo; and &ldquo;efficiently&rdquo; a second language (L2) speaker can speak on &ldquo;a range of topics in real time&rdquo;. While fluency may denote a degree of proficiency, it does not automatically imply \u003Cem\u003Eaccuracy\u003C\u002Fem\u003E &ndash; the ability to produce grammatically correct sentences &ndash; nor does it imply grammatical range.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHow important \u003Cem\u003Eare\u003C\u002Fem\u003E accuracy and grammatical range? That depends on the speaker&rsquo;s needs. If they simply wish to converse in social settings, their focus may be solely on achieving fluency, but if the L2 is required for business or academia, accuracy and range are crucial as communications full of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.britishcouncilfoundation.id\u002Fen\u002Fenglish\u002Farticles\u002Ffluency-vs-accuracy\"\u003Eerrors may be seen as unprofessional\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8r5v"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpdfs.semanticscholar.org\u002Ff05e\u002Fe9d0bc97b76e799ebf59e65ef3293ed5f835.pdf\"\u003EThese errors can include\u003C\u002Fa\u003E literal word-for-word translation from their native language (&ldquo;I go in Spain&rdquo;), and language switch (&ldquo;I want eat \u003Cem\u003Eringo\u003C\u002Fem\u003E&rdquo;). Bungled verb tenses, prepositions, plurals, and articles are a natural, even essential, part of the learning process.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou might also enjoy:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life\"\u003EThe man bringing languages back to life \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20181030-the-10-personality-traits-that-english-cant-name\"\u003EThe 10 personality traits that English cannot name \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20160811-the-amazing-benefits-of-being-bilingual\"\u003EThe amazing benefits of being bilingual \u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany learners, however, fall into the trap of assuming that because they are understood, their speech is &ldquo;perfect&rdquo;. And it isn&rsquo;t only the speaker who glosses over mistakes; in the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fpublication\u002F301296350_Fluency_in_second_language_assessment\"\u003EHandbook of Second Language Assessment,\u003C\u002Fa\u003E Nivja de Jong &ndash; senior lecturer at the Leiden University Centre for Linguistics &ndash; argues that grammatical errors usually won&rsquo;t prevent comprehension on the part of the listener, who is automatically able to &ldquo;edit out&rdquo; mistakes. In English, a sentence like &ldquo;I have 17 years&rdquo; is incorrect, yet one nonetheless understands that the speaker wants to say that he is 17 years old. Furthermore, friends and teachers tend to encourage L2 learners rather than discourage them, which may also contribute to inflated self-assessment.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI think of the popular memes comparing how we envision a story or \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fi.pinimg.com\u002Foriginals\u002F73\u002F3a\u002F9a\u002F733a9a5311a0f89d3ffa7baffea66bd9.jpg\"\u003Escene in our head\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, to the way we tell it or paint it. Those first crucial years of learning a language, you may be thinking in glorious brush strokes but speaking in scribbles.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8qvs"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ESo when can someone say they &ldquo;speak&rdquo; a language? That&rsquo;s the million-dollar question. Can someone consider themselves a Spanish speaker if they&rsquo;re conversational but often can&rsquo;t understand native speakers because they &ldquo;talk too fast&rdquo;? If they use only two verb tenses and every sentence contains mistakes?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe answer may be less &ldquo;yes\u002Fno&rdquo; and more &ldquo;how well?&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELuckily, scales for measuring spoken fluency and overall proficiency exist. &ldquo;Fluency is an abstract concept, so we assign observable variables,&rdquo; explains Daniel Morgan. Two of the most reliable factors are &ldquo;speech rate&rdquo; and &ldquo;utterance length&rdquo;. Speech rate can be defined as how much (effective) language you&rsquo;re producing over time, for example how many syllables per minute. Utterance length is, as an average, how much you can produce between disfluencies (e.g. a pause or hesitation). You could look at accuracy as being subsumed into fluency, in terms of grammatical accuracy, lexical choice, pronunciation, and precision.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDe Jong describes the unconscious process any speaker goes through before speaking: conceptualising what to say, formulating how to say it, and, finally, articulating the appropriate sounds. All of this takes place in roughly six syllables per second. A speaker of a second language who needs to convert their thoughts into an unfamiliar language faces an even greater challenge in meeting these strict time constraints. They must also often overcome inhibition and pronunciation challenges. Accuracy may still be lacking at this stage, but make no mistake &ndash; achieving L2 fluency is a colossal feat.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Council of Europe&rsquo;s \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.coe.int\u002Fen\u002Fweb\u002Fcommon-european-framework-reference-languages\u002Flevel-descriptions\"\u003ECommon European Framework of References (CEFR) for Languages\u003C\u002Fa\u003E groups language learners into concrete proficiency levels, where fluency and accuracy are just two of many examined criteria. The CEFR &ndash; \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.coe.int\u002Fen\u002Fweb\u002Fcommon-european-framework-reference-languages\u002Ftable-2-cefr-3.3-common-reference-levels-self-assessment-grid\"\u003Eavailable in 40 languages\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; divides proficiency into six &ldquo;can do&rdquo; levels &ndash; A1, A2, B1, B2, C1, and C2. A corresponds to &ldquo;Basic&rdquo; levels, B to &ldquo;Independent&rdquo;, and C to &ldquo;Proficient.&rdquo; Observable skills include:\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA1:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Capabilities range include basic introductions and answering questions about personal details provided the listener speaks slowly and is willing to cooperate.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA2\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Can describe in simple terms aspects of his\u002Fher past, environment and matters related to his\u002Fher immediate needs and perform routine tasks requiring basic exchanges of information.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB1:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Can deal with most daily life situations in the country where the language is spoken. Can describe experiences, dreams and ambitions and give brief reasons for opinions and goals.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB2:\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E Can understand the themes of complex texts on both concrete and abstract topics and will have achieved a degree of fluency and spontaneity, which makes interaction with native speakers possible without significant strain for either party.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC1\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Can understand a wide range of longer texts and recognise subtleties and implicit meaning; producing clear, well-structured and detailed text on complex subjects, showing controlled use of organisational patterns, connectors and cohesive devices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC2\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E: Can understand virtually everything heard or read, expressing themselves spontaneously, very fluently and precisely, while differentiating finer shades of meaning even in highly complex situations.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGeraint Thomas, a Cambridge English speaking exam team leader, explains: &ldquo;We look at things like cohesion, response rate, discourse management, and pronunciation, but each variable has sub-variables. You can break pronunciation down into \u003Cem\u003Estress\u003C\u002Fem\u003E and \u003Cem\u003Eindividual sounds\u003C\u002Fem\u003E.&rdquo; He emphasises that the progression is gradual. &ldquo;You can expect a good B2 candidate to have certain things under control; the present tense, maybe. However, they might not have their second conditional, and you&rsquo;re aware that this is a progressive thing.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p07m8r18"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThomas adds that individual second language speakers can display different strengths: &ldquo;You can get students who are very accurate but so afraid of making mistakes that their fluency suffers and others who throw themselves into something, who are quite fluent, but their language is full of mistakes.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to research from the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fsupport.cambridgeenglish.org\u002Fhc\u002Fen-gb\u002Farticles\u002F202838506-Guided-learning-hours\"\u003EUniversity of Cambridge English Language Assessment\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, it takes 200 guided hours for a motivated learner to advance from one level to the next. Key word, \u003Cem\u003Emotivated\u003C\u002Fem\u003E: language acquisition varies dramatically between individuals. Is the learner open to new structures? Will they build upon what they&rsquo;ve already learned instead of clinging to basic &ldquo;good enough&rdquo; grammar? Will they commit to consistent study and practice? Bottom line: there are many steps between &ldquo;The pen is on the table&rdquo; and penning a perfect thesis on a piece of literature.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProficiency scales provide an excellent gauge for assessing L2 ability, but I believe that the quickest, dirtiest fluency and accuracy &ldquo;tests&rdquo; are real-life situations with native speakers. How smooth and lengthy are your interactions in your L2? Do you avoid or &ldquo;blank&rdquo; at certain topics and situations because you don&rsquo;t have the words? Do you find yourself grasping for &ldquo;key words&rdquo; and content yourself with understanding &ldquo;the sense&rdquo; rather than the entirety of the conversation? How well can you understand a film without subtitles or read a book without a dictionary? If you write an email and ask a native speaker to proofread it, how many errors will they find?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs for me, while my Italian grammatical range has improved dramatically in my nine years in Italy, as a writer I yearn for flawless, native-like accuracy and syntax. I&rsquo;m not there yet, and there are many days where I despair that I never will be.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnd then I remind myself that learning a second language is like entering into a marriage. You think you know your partner when you put the ring on their finger, but it&rsquo;s only the beginning, and the commitment is for life. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.ieatmypigeon.com\u002F\"\u003EEva Sandoval\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is an Italian-American writer who has been based in Italy since 2010. Her travel, food, and culture writing has appeared in The Telegraph, CNN Travel, Fodor&rsquo;s Travel Guides\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, and HuffPo Travel as well as various luxury hotel and airline magazines. \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIf you liked this story, \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fpages.emails.bbc.com\u002Fsubscribe\u002F?ocid=fut.bbc.email.we.email-signup\"\u003Esign up for the weekly bbc.com features newsletter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, called &ldquo;The Essential List&rdquo;. A handpicked selection of stories from BBC Future, Culture, Worklife, and Travel, delivered to your inbox every Friday.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning-8"}],"collection":["future\u002Fcolumn\u002Fin-depth"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2019-09-04T00:00:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"How do we measure language fluency?","headlineShort":"What does being ‘fluent’ really mean?","image":["p07mbx7q"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":false,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5e98214ca91acb5c91f3c9a4"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"future","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":["tag\u002Flanguage"],"summaryLong":"There are many ways of categorising someone’s linguistic skills, but the concept of fluency is hard to define.","summaryShort":"There are many ways of measuring someone’s language proficiency","tag":["tag\u002Flanguage"],"creationDateTime":"2019-09-03T15:55:25.944098Z","entity":"article","guid":"65357b2c-6a3d-4547-9f03-f68211327fe0","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning","modifiedDateTime":"2019-10-04T14:11:31.366112Z","project":"future","slug":"20190903-linguistic-fluency-proficiency-second-language-learning","cacheLastUpdated":1587443132957},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life","_id":"5e98209ea91acb5c91ee1af1","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Falex-rawlings"],"bodyIntro":"Ghil’ad Zuckermann has found that resurrecting lost languages may bring many benefits to indigenous populations – with knock-on effects for their health and happiness.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ELike many people in Australia, Professor Ghil&rsquo;ad Zuckermann is a regular contributor to the fund to save the Tasmanian Devil. The Tasmanian Devil, which Zuckermann remarks is an &ldquo;ugly animal&rdquo;, is listed as endangered, along with much of the unique and beautiful wildlife that makes Australia such a distinctive and enigmatic place. Yet animal life is not the only thing that has struggled to keep up with the pressures of modern life down under.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Before European colonisers arrived, Australia used to be one of the most linguistically diverse areas in the world, boasting around 250 different languages","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWhile Australia may be famous the world over for its biodiversity, for a linguistics professor like Zuckermann, the country has another allure: its languages. Before European colonisers arrived, Australia used to be one of the most linguistically diverse areas in the world, boasting around 250 different languages. Due in part to Australia&rsquo;s long geographic isolation, many of these had developed unique grammatical structures and concepts that were unknown to languages in other parts of the world.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne of these is a language called Guugu Yimithirr, spoken in the north of Queensland, which gave the world the word \"kangaroo\". It&rsquo;s also made remarkable by the fact that unlike languages like English, it does not make use of ego-centric positioning systems such as \"left\" and \"right\". Instead, all speakers of Guugu Yimithirr have an in-built compass in their brain that allows them to always know where is north, south, east and west. Therefore, they have no need to talk about the \"left tap\" or the \"right tap\". Instead, they just refer to the \"north tap\" or the \"south tap\".\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBut according to the 2016 Australian census, Guugu Yimithirr has just 775 native speakers alive today, with numbers on the decline. Of the 250 languages spoken before settlers arrived, today all but 13 of them are considered to be \"highly endangered\" &ndash; a fact that is often overlooked.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0742v5z"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I believe that most people care more about animals that are endangered than about languages that are endangered,&rdquo; Zuckerman explains. &ldquo;The reason is that animals are tangible. You can touch a koala, even though in the wild you&rsquo;d be crazy to do so because she can kill you with her claws. But koalas are cute. Languages, however, are not tangible. They are abstract. People understand the importance of biodiversity far more than that of linguistic diversity\u003Cstrong\u003E.&rdquo; \u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYet for Zuckermann, preserving linguistic diversity is hugely important. For indigenous communities in Australia and worldwide that are still grappling with the legacy of colonisation, being able to speak their ancestral language is about empowerment and reclaiming their identity. It may even carry significant consequences for their mental health.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cul\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20140606-why-we-must-save-dying-languages\"\u003EWhy we must save dying tongues\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20190226-how-your-language-reflects-the-senses-you-use\"\u003EHow your language reflects the senses you use\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003Cli\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Fstory\u002F20181030-the-10-personality-traits-that-english-cant-name\"\u003EThe 10 personality traits the English cannot name\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E \u003C\u002Ful\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGhil&rsquo;ad Zuckermann first visited Australia in 2004. He felt so overcome with love for what he describes as the most beautiful country he&rsquo;d ever seen that he decided he wanted to do something to help it. As a linguistics professor from Israel, the son of a Holocaust survivor, and a specialist at the time in the analysis of the Hebrew language revival, he quickly identified an area where he could have an impact: the revival and empowerment of Aboriginal languages and cultures.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZuckermann first established the trans-disciplinary field of enquiry called &ldquo;Revivalistics&rdquo;, which focuses on supporting the survival, revival and reinvigoration of endangered and extinct languages all around the world. These range from languages such as Hebrew, Welsh, Cornish and Irish, to Hawaiian, North American languages like Wampanoag and Myaamia, and many others.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0742vnr"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAs an Israeli, Zuckermann grew up a native speaker of Modern Hebrew, arguably the world&rsquo;s most successful example of language revival to date. Hebrew was extinct for almost 2,000 years until Zionist language revivalists began to bring it back into use in the late 19th Century. They achieved this by adapting the ancient language of the Torah so that it could be suitable for modern life. It would eventually become the mother tongue of all Jews in the new state of Israel, founded in 1948.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZuckermann&rsquo;s expertise and personal experience with Modern Hebrew greatly informs his work in Australia today, precisely because he takes a critical view of it. He argues that the language spoken natively by millions of people in Israel today and that they call Hebrew is not, and could not be, the same language of the Bible.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The Jews did not manage to revive the language of Isaiah. It is simply impossible to revive a language as it used to be.&rdquo; Instead, Zuckermann explains that Modern Hebrew, which he controversially refers to as \"Israeli\", is a hybrid language, drawing on the influences that Jewish migrants brought with them to Israel from their native languages, such as Yiddish, Polish, Russian and Arabic. Over the course of generations, these blended together to shape the language in its modern form. According to Zuckermann, this should not be seen as a problem. These changes are a natural and necessary part of the process of reviving a language.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0742yfk"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I take into consideration the speaker more than the language. A speaker of Yiddish could not get rid of their Yiddish Weltanschauung or mindset, even though they hated Yiddish and wanted to speak Hebrew. But the moment a person understands the importance of the native speaker at the expense of linguistic purism and authenticity of the language, that person can be a good revivalist.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESleeping beauties\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMuch of Zuckermann&rsquo;s work in Australia has centred on Barngarla, a dead language &ndash; Zuckermann prefers the term &ldquo;sleeping beauty&rdquo; &ndash; that was spoken in the rural areas of southern Australia between the cities of Port Augusta, Port Lincoln and Whyalla. The last native speaker, Moonie Davis, passed away in 1960. Yet when Zuckerman reached out to the Barngarla community and proposed that he help revive their language and their culture, he was amazed by their response. &ldquo;We have been waiting for you for 50 years,&rdquo; they told him.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EZuckermann&rsquo;s starting point was a dictionary written by a Lutheran missionary called Robert Sch&uuml;rmann in 1844. In 2011, Zuckermann began making regular trips to Barngarla country to run language revival workshops. Together, and with Zuckermann&rsquo;s help and guidance, the Barngarla community built upon the knowledge stored within Sch&uuml;rmann&rsquo;s 1844 dictionary. They pooled together what they could remember of words they&rsquo;d heard their parents and grandparents saying.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThey also held discussions about how to devise appropriate words that could apply to modern life. Should Barngarla follow English&rsquo;s precedent and refer to the computer using the metaphor of &lsquo;computing&rsquo; something? Or should they instead look to Mandarin Chinese, whose word 电脑 (di&agrave;nnǎo) literally means &ldquo;electric brain&rdquo;?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe result is modern-day Barngarla, a language that has been revived in a form that is as close as possible to the Barngarla that was spoken before its last native speaker died out. Yet inevitably, as with the case of Modern Hebrew, it will never fully be the same. Too much time has passed, and there has been too much influence from the colonial language, in this case English, for today&rsquo;s Barngarla to be a carbon copy. It too is a hybrid language, yet one that the Barngarla community can feel proud to speak once more. For Zuckermann, there is nothing wrong with that. In fact, quite the opposite: &ldquo;Hybridity results in new linguistic diversity.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELinguicide\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Linguicide&rdquo; &ndash; the killing of language &ndash; sits amongst the 10 forms of genocide that are recognised by the United Nations. The Barngarla language did not die out in 1960 solely due to natural causes. Like many Aboriginal languages, in the early to mid-20th Century it was actively destroyed and subjected to the cruel and imperialistic policies of the Australian government at the time, who removed children from their mothers and sent them to boarding schools thousands of miles away. There, they learned English and quickly forgot their mother tongue. If they ever returned to their ancestral homelands, they found themselves unable to communicate with their own families, as they no longer shared a common language.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0742wy3"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ELavinia Richards is one of the \"stolen generation\". She remembers the trauma of being forcibly separated from her mother by the Australian authorities and forced to speak a foreign language &ndash; English. When the Barngarla community released a CD of stories and songs of Barngarla people affected by the \"stolen generation\" in June 2018, she included on it a poem that she wrote about a flower she saw that reminded her of her mother, a reminder of a life that was denied to her because she was born speaking the wrong language.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor Zuckermann, there are three reasons why people should support language revival. The first is the simple ethical matter of righting the wrongs of colonial linguistic supremacy. Zuckermann states that the very fact that the Australian government at the time actively tried to destroy Australia&rsquo;s unique linguistic diversity, driven perhaps by the racist notions of politicians such as Anthony Forster, who in 1843 declared &ldquo;the natives would be sooner civilised if their language was extinct&rdquo;, is convincing enough for him.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, Zuckermann&rsquo;s second reason is utilitarian. Language revival is about far more than just communication. He argues that it is about &ldquo;culture, cultural autonomy, intellectual sovereignty, spirituality, well-being, and the soul&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"When you lose your language, you lose your soul - Ghil&rsquo;ad Zuckermann","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;When you lose your language, you lose your soul. When you revive your language, you don&rsquo;t only revive its sounds, its words, its morphemes and its phonemes. You revive the whole shebang.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver his many years of working in language revival, Zuckermann has become increasingly convinced of a clear trend. He believes that amongst Aboriginal communities that have reclaimed their ancestral language, he has observed greatly improved physical and mental health. He sees a sharp drop in incidences of suicide, alcoholism, addiction and diabetes &ndash; problems that unfortunately are rife amongst Aboriginal people across Australia.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese are only anecdotal observations but in 2017, he began a five-year study to see whether he could find hard evidence to support the theory. Should he be proven right, he believes that this should give the Australian government enough cause to support language revival programmes across the country through healthcare funding from tax payers&rsquo; money.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0742xjw"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EA preliminary investigation in 2007 from the University of Oxford, University of British Columbia and the University of Victoria in Canada seems to support Zuckermann&rsquo;s claims. By analysing Canadian census data, the researchers discovered that youth suicide rates &ldquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.erudit.org\u002Fen\u002Fjournals\u002Frs\u002F2007-v48-n3-rs2283\u002F018011ar\u002F\"\u003Eeffectively dropped to zero in the few communities where at least half of the members reported a conversational level of their &lsquo;Native&rsquo; language\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I really believe that billions of dollars in Australia have been wasted on stupid, medically approved programmes. I can prove qualitatively and quantitatively that language revival results in better health,\" Zuckermann says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;You kill the language of an Aboriginal community, you cause depression. You cause depression, you cause people to lose their will to take care of their body.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe third and final reason Zuckermann cites for supporting language revival is aesthetic. In other words, the co-existence of so many distinct and unique languages is beautiful. Australia&rsquo;s multilingualism is like the human reflection of the biodiversity for which the country is so well known. Yet Zuckermann is aware that of all of his arguments, this is the one that may meet its toughest reception amongst the wider public.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor Candace Kaleimamoowahinekapu Galla, a native Hawaiian and associate professor at the University of British Columbia, speaking her ancestral language and promoting its use amongst her fellow Hawaiians is about something simple, yet fundamental. It&rsquo;s about pride. &ldquo;But not in an egotistical way,&rdquo; she is quick to clarify. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a humbling pride. It&rsquo;s about accessing documents, newspapers or stories from the 1800s and understanding them on a different level to just reading them through an English translation.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-14"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0742xwq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20190320-the-man-bringing-dead-languages-back-to-life-15"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EGalla describes the Hawaiian language as the foundation of everything distinguishing about Hawaiian culture. She believes that even the famous Hula dance, which has risen to the status of something of a global phenomenon, is impossible to truly perform without understanding Hawaiian, the lyric and the motion behind the lyric. Without an appreciation for those things, you are &ldquo;just learning choreography&rdquo;, according to Galla. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t dance Hula without Hawaiian. You can dance, but it&rsquo;s not Hula.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELooking to the future, Zuckermann has grand plans. After his decisions to found Revivalistics and to work with the Barngarla community, he says that his next step is to spread the message far and wide.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESince running his first online open-access course on language revival in 2014, he has so far had more than 11,000 participants in 188 countries, including in Afghanistan, Syria, and countries where genocide and linguicide are common.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I want to reach people who are not academic. People who are language activists, but who do not go to university and do not have money to do things. People who would like to revive their language.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E--\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EAlex Rawlings is a polyglot and writer, who in 2012 was named Britain&rsquo;s Most Multilingual Student after being tested for fluency in 11 languages. His most recent book is From Amourette to Żal: Bizarre and Beautiful Words from Around Europe.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EJoin 900,000+ Future fans by liking us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.facebook.com\u002FBBCFuture\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EFacebook\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E, or follow us on&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FBBC_Future\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETwitter\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E&nbsp;or&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.instagram.com\u002Fbbcfuture_official\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EInstagram\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E